When looking at crime studies it's always important to look at HOW things are being compared, not just the who, what, when, where and why.
But, if those numbers were for 2 different towns it makes things foggy. Q: Why would you use 2 different time frames for 2 different towns?
For instance, if there're 15 thefts over 5 years in a town & then 24 in the same town in following 2 years you may conclude increased theft.
However, similar studies with different perimeters for study, specifically that of time, doesn't render one or the other without value.
Yes, a study range of anything over 13 years is odd, but not unheard of. It makes it challenging to compare similar studies w/other ranges.
